Fruitflies

TASK

What is the expected lifespan of flies in the low activity group and with thorax lengths of 0.75 and 0.85mm?

The lifespan of flies in the high activity group with thorax lengths of 0.75 and 0.85mm?

The lifespan of flies in the isolated activity group with thorax lengths of 0.75 and 0.85mm?

Youll need to look at the coefficients produced from the model and calculate a prediction. You can check youre in the right ballpark by looking at the plot above.

Look again at the model.

summary(ff1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = longevity ~ thorax + activity, data = fruitfly)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -26.108  -7.014  -1.101   6.234  30.265 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   -48.749     10.850  -4.493 1.65e-05 ***
## thorax        134.341     12.731  10.552  < 2e-16 ***
## activityone     2.637      2.984   0.884   0.3786    
## activitymany    4.139      3.027   1.367   0.1741    
## activitylow    -7.015      2.981  -2.353   0.0203 *  
## activityhigh  -20.004      3.016  -6.632 1.05e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 10.54 on 118 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6527, Adjusted R-squared:  0.638 
## F-statistic: 44.36 on 5 and 118 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Lets manually work out the longevity of these flies. Predicted longevity = intercept + thorax length * fitted coefficient for slope + low activity coefficient.

Thus, in the low activity group with size of 0.75mm

Predicted longevity = -48.749 + 134.341 * 0.75 -7.015 = 44.99 days

Check this looks sensible on the plot. If youve got the calculation badly wrong youll see it.

The low activity group with size of 0.85mm

Predicted longevity = -48.749 + 134.341 * 0.85 -7.015 = 58.43 days

The high activity group with size of 0.75mm

Predicted longevity = -48.749 + 134.341 * 0.75 -20.004 = 32.00 days

The high activity group with size of 0.85mm

Predicted longevity = -48.749 + 134.341 * 0.85 -20.004 = 45.44 days

Some of you may be wondering were the isolated treatment group is in the table. The other 4 treatment groups are compared against the isolated group, so its in the intercept.

The isolated activity group with size of 0.75mm

Predicted longevity = -48.749 + 134.341 * 0.75 = 52.01 days

The isolated activity group with size of 0.85mm

Predicted longevity = -48.749 + 134.341 * 0.85 = 65.44 days

Using predict

Of course, there is also a way to get R to calculate this for you. We can use the predict function (see ?predict.lm for help). We can take the ff1 object we created for the regression model and ask predict to give us values for new data. First we need to create a data frame with the new data, with exactly the same column names and data types as the fruitfly dataframe (i.e.the thorax column as numeric and the activity column as a 5 level factor). Lets do this for the low activity group with thorax sizes of 0.75 and 0.85.

new.fly.df <- data.frame(
  thorax=c(0.75,0.85),
  activity=factor(c("low","low"),levels=c("isolated","one","many","low","high"))
  ) #I've split this across lines to make it a little easier to read
new.fly.df
##   thorax activity
## 1   0.75      low
## 2   0.85      low

Then we need to feed this new dataframe, plus the model, to predict

predict(ff1, newdata = new.fly.df)
##        1        2 
## 44.99170 58.42583

This is the same as we calculated manually. We could either create a new data frame for each of the tasks above, or one big dataframe with them all in.

Hydrolases

Glycoside hydrolases able to metabolise starch were isolated from two different species of bacteria (A and B) and their activity in enzyme units (U or mol/min) measured across a range of salt concentrations (percentage NaCl w/v).

The data are within the file hydrolase.txt

First plot out hydrolase activity vs salt concentration from the 2 species. Do these appear to have the same or different slopes in the two species?

Perform an analyse to determine whether the slopes are statistically different.

Read the file in and check it

hydrolase <- read.table("hydrolase.txt",header=TRUE)
head(hydrolase)
##   species salt activity
## 1       A  0.4     2.60
## 2       A  0.4     2.73
## 3       A  0.4     2.69
## 4       A  0.4     2.69
## 5       A  0.4     2.80
## 6       A  0.4     2.24

Define species as a factor

hydrolase$species <- factor(hydrolase$species, levels=c("A","B")) 
#levels argument redundant, since levels are assigned alphabetically, but good practice

What do they look like? We looked at a similar example for fruitfly. One way to plot this is as follows.

hydro.plot1 <- ggplot(data=hydrolase, aes(x=salt, y=activity))

hydro.plot1 + geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(~species) + 
  xlab("Salt concentration (w/v)") + ylab("Hydrolase activity (U)")

#you could also add geom_smooth(method="lm") to add a line if you wanted

These look like the slopes are different for the two groups, ie an interaction.

Fit a model and test interaction. Only the interaction term will be tested by drop1 if it exists in the model, not the main effects.

hydro.mod <- lm(activity ~ species*salt,data=hydrolase)
summary(hydro.mod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = activity ~ species * salt, data = hydrolase)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -0.43883 -0.17967 -0.01208  0.16021  0.39283 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)     2.9983     0.1118  26.809  < 2e-16 ***
## speciesB       -0.0025     0.1582  -0.016    0.987    
## salt           -0.8912     0.1021  -8.729 3.71e-11 ***
## speciesB:salt   1.2858     0.1444   8.906 2.10e-11 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.2237 on 44 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.917,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.9113 
## F-statistic:   162 on 3 and 44 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
drop1(hydro.mod,test="F")
## Single term deletions
## 
## Model:
## activity ~ species * salt
##              Df Sum of Sq    RSS      AIC F value    Pr(>F)    
## <none>                    2.2015 -139.939                      
## species:salt  1    3.9681 6.1696  -92.475  79.308 2.102e-11 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Here the summary table and plot suggest an interaction, and drop1 confirms it.

Finally, you can check the model looks ok with plot(hydro.mod). You wouldnt put a plot like this in a report, its simply a diagnostic plot to check your model is sensible.

Birthweight

TASK

Generate a minimal adequate model from the following maximal model

lm(Birthweight ~ (Gestation + smoker + mppwt)^2, data = birthweight)

birthweight <- read.csv("birthweight.csv",header=TRUE)

Start with the maximal model

bw.max <- lm(Birthweight ~ (Gestation + smoker + mppwt)^2, data = birthweight)

Can we drop anything, and what should we drop first?

drop1(bw.max, test="F")
## Single term deletions
## 
## Model:
## Birthweight ~ (Gestation + smoker + mppwt)^2
##                  Df Sum of Sq    RSS      AIC F value Pr(>F)
## <none>                        24.842  -8.0562               
## Gestation:smoker  1   0.75225 25.594  -8.8032  1.0599 0.3103
## Gestation:mppwt   1   0.02930 24.871 -10.0067  0.0413 0.8402
## smoker:mppwt      1   1.49853 26.340  -7.5961  2.1113 0.1551

None of the terms are significant, but Gestation:mppwt is the least significant so we drop this first. We can do this with the update function.

bw.mod.1 <- update(bw.max, .~. - Gestation:mppwt)

Then use drop1 again on this new model

drop1(bw.mod.1, test="F")
## Single term deletions
## 
## Model:
## Birthweight ~ Gestation + smoker + mppwt + Gestation:smoker + 
##     smoker:mppwt
##                  Df Sum of Sq    RSS      AIC F value Pr(>F)
## <none>                        24.871 -10.0067               
## Gestation:smoker  1   0.72533 25.596 -10.7993  1.0499 0.3124
## smoker:mppwt      1   1.61118 26.482  -9.3703  2.3321 0.1355

Next term to drop is Gestation:smoker. Take your time to keep track of each model name and term to be dropped. Its easy to make mistakes during this.

bw.mod.2 <- update(bw.mod.1, .~. - Gestation:smoker)
drop1(bw.mod.2, test="F")
## Single term deletions
## 
## Model:
## Birthweight ~ Gestation + smoker + mppwt + smoker:mppwt
##              Df Sum of Sq    RSS      AIC F value    Pr(>F)    
## <none>                    25.596 -10.7993                      
## Gestation     1   28.5895 54.186  18.6994 41.3267 1.654e-07 ***
## smoker:mppwt  1    2.6493 28.246  -8.6628  3.8296   0.05793 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

smoker:mppwt isnt quite significant. Drop it.

bw.mod.3 <- update(bw.mod.2, .~. - smoker:mppwt)
drop1(bw.mod.3, test="F")
## Single term deletions
## 
## Model:
## Birthweight ~ Gestation + smoker + mppwt
##           Df Sum of Sq    RSS     AIC F value    Pr(>F)    
## <none>                 28.246 -8.6628                      
## Gestation  1   26.1055 54.351 16.8274 35.1209 7.185e-07 ***
## smoker     1    4.5886 32.834 -4.3405  6.1732   0.01749 *  
## mppwt      1    3.8009 32.046 -5.3603  5.1135   0.02955 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Everything is now significant, i.e.nothing can be dropped and weve arrived at the minimal model.

We can check what it looks like with summary(bw.mod.3) and plot(bw.mod.3):

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Birthweight ~ Gestation + smoker + mppwt, data = birthweight)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -1.3824 -0.6246 -0.1033  0.7158  1.9276 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) -7.164740   2.107344  -3.400   0.0016 ** 
## Gestation    0.313421   0.052887   5.926 7.19e-07 ***
## smoker      -0.665279   0.267762  -2.485   0.0175 *  
## mppwt        0.019819   0.008764   2.261   0.0295 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.8622 on 38 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6104, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5796 
## F-statistic: 19.84 on 3 and 38 DF,  p-value: 6.635e-08

This is relatively OK given we have a fairly small number of data points.

Alternate approach

You can also use the step function to cut out some of the steps, but it will keep the smoker:mppwt and has to be nudged along from there.

#starting again from the maximal model
bw.step.1 <- step(bw.max)
drop1(bw.step.1, test ="F") # still has smoker:mppwt

bw.step.2 <- update(bw.step.1, .~. - smoker:mppwt)
drop1(bw.step.2, test="F")

This gets us to the same minimal adequate model as before.

Comment on the importance of mothers prepregnancy weight (mppwt).

Freom the model, mppwt (mothers weight) is statistically significant at the 5% level but not the 1% level. This is one measure of significance. But biological significance might also be considered if you want to ask how important is mothers weight for birth weight. One way to do this is to predict from the model what weight of baby we expect from two mothers of different weights. The summary of the model (summary(bw.mod.3)) give us the formula of the model:

birthweight ~ -7.165 + 0.313*Gestation (weeks) -0.665*smoker + 0.0198*mppwt

We just need to find some sensible values to plus into the model.

First, whats a typical gestation time?

summary(birthweight$Gestation)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   33.00   38.00   39.50   39.19   41.00   45.00

Lets take the median gestation time of 39.5 weeks.

Second, what are sensible weights to give the model for a light mother and a heavy mother?

summary(birthweight$mppwt)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    99.0   115.0   125.0   125.9   135.0   170.0

Using the interquartile range we could use a value for a light mother as 115lbs and a heavy mother as 135lbs. The language of light and heavy is problematic and comes with some social baggage. By picking the interquartile range (containing half of the women in the study), these are women who are both within the typical range of weights, but just a bit lighter than average or a bit heavier than average.

Lets make things a bit easier by predicting birth weight from non-smokers, since that term will go to zero in the model (-0.665*0 = 0). So for intercept + gestation + mothers age:

A 115 lb mother giving birth at 39.5 weeks could expect a baby of

-7.165 + 0.313 * 39.5 + 0.0198 * 115 = 7.48 lbs

A 135 lb mother giving birth at 39.5 weeks could expect a baby of

-7.165 + 0.313 * 39.5 + 0.0198 * 135 = 7.87 lbs

So theres some difference (~0.4 lbs), but not huge.

The same approach for gestation time, taking the median for mothers weight and the interquartile range for gestation time as 38 - 41 weeks, gives a bigger difference (nearly 1 lb). Its more obvious biological effect that the longer a baby grows inside mum the bigger it gets when it finally comes out.

-7.165 + 0.313 * 38 + 0.0198 * 125 = 7.20 lbs

-7.165 + 0.313 * 41 + 0.0198 * 125 = 8.14 lbs

(You can also investigate predict.lm, which can take a data frame of dummy values without having to manually do the prediction.)

Some of you have probably tried plotting the model, which is the challenge of plotting Birthweight ~ Gestation + mppwt + smoker, i.e.how is birthweight affected by gestation time and mothers weight and whether shes a smoker or not. I struggled to come up with a very convincing plot, largely because the effect of mothers weight is fairly small. In the material, we saw how to use ggplot to visualise Birthweight ~ Gestation + smoker so now we need to work out how to add mppwt to this. One way, which uses code that youve (mostly) already learnt, is to use colour for mppwt.

#what to plot
bw.plot2 <- ggplot(data = birthweight, aes(x=Gestation, y=Birthweight, color=mppwt))

#how to plot it (this is just the code from the workshop)
bw.plot2 + geom_point(size=4) + facet_wrap(~smoker) +
  xlab("Gestation (weeks)") + ylab("Birthweight (lbs)") +
  theme_bw() +scale_color_gradient(low="blue", high="red")

Haemoglobin

TASK

The file haemoglobin.csv contains data on haemoglobin levels in the blood from alpha thalasaemia carriers and normal controls (neither have disease symptoms).

  • sex; male/female

  • phenotype; alpha_carrier/normal

  • pcv; packed cell volume (percentage)

  • rbc; red blood cell count (1012/L)

  • lymph; white blood cell count (106/L)

  • hb; haemoglobin concentration (g/dL)

Using hb as the response variable explore which, if any, of the other variables is associated with haemoglobin concentration. Produce a table of your model and a plot of your results and briefly comment on the biological interpretation. This provides some more practice of the approach and follows in the same way as before.

Read the data in with haem <- read.csv("haemoglobin.csv").

summary(haem)
##      sex             phenotype              pcv             rbc      
##  Length:197         Length:197         Min.   :22.10   Min.   :2.41  
##  Class :character   Class :character   1st Qu.:33.30   1st Qu.:4.69

##                                        Mean   :36.72   Mean   :5.04  
##                                        3rd Qu.:39.30   3rd Qu.:5.43

##  Min.   :10.30   Min.   : 8.56  
##  1st Qu.:37.00   1st Qu.:10.94  
##  Median :41.54   Median :11.93  
##  Mean   :43.57   Mean   :12.10  
##  3rd Qu.:46.00   3rd Qu.:13.18  
##  Max.   :87.00   Max.   :16.41

Set sex and phenotype as factors

haem$sex <- factor(haem$sex)
haem$phenotype <- factor(haem$phenotype)

Remember that hb is the dependent variable. To quickly check it looks roughly normally distributed you can use hist(haem$hb) or similar.

Now we can work out which explanatory variables are important. The easiest thing to do is to set up a maximal model with all the other variables and their 2-way interactions as explanatory variables.

heam.max1 <- lm(hb ~ (sex + phenotype +pcv + rbc + lymph)^2, data = haem)

Quickly check the model looks sensible with plot(heam.max1)

Ill use the step approach to save some code, but its fine if you want to go all the way through with update.

haem.m1 <- step(heam.max1)
drop1(haem.m1, test="F")
## Single term deletions
## 
## Model:
## hb ~ sex + pcv + lymph
##        Df Sum of Sq    RSS     AIC  F value  Pr(>F)    
## <none>               99.53 -126.50                     
## sex     1      2.85 102.38 -122.94   5.5324 0.01967 *  
## pcv     1    372.69 472.22  178.22 722.6896 < 2e-16 ***
## lymph   1      1.07 100.60 -126.39   2.0771 0.15114    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

step has done the hard work but we we still need to remove lymph

haem.m2 <- update(haem.m1, .~. - lymph)
drop1(haem.m2, test = "F")
## Single term deletions
## 
## Model:
## hb ~ sex + pcv
##        Df Sum of Sq    RSS     AIC  F value  Pr(>F)    
## <none>              100.60 -126.39                     
## sex     1      2.36 102.96 -123.83   4.5513 0.03415 *  
## pcv     1    391.47 492.07  184.34 754.9215 < 2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

So weve arrived at a minimal model since nothing can be removed from this. Lets look at it with summary.

summary(haem.m2)

Sex and pcv are both significant. None of the interactions are. The alpha thalasaemia genotype is not significant (though remember this is just between carriers and controls, there are no homozygote, affected individuals).

Sex F1,194 = 4.55, p < 0.05. pcv F1,194 = 754.92, p < 0.001. To get the F values use the output from drop1. Each term has one degree of freedom associated with it. The residual 194 degrees of freedom you can see from summary((haem.m2) or anova((haem.m2).

To plot this out

haem.plot1 <- ggplot(data=haem, aes(x=pcv,y=hb, color=sex))

haem.plot1 + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~sex) +
  xlab("Packed cell volume (%age)") + ylab("Haemoglobin concentration (g/dL)")

Here you can see a really strong effect of packed cell volume on haemoglobin concentration, which makes sense. However, the direct effect of sex on hb is quite subtle. From the model, being a male increases your haemoglobin concentration by only 0.23 g/dL . This is small compared to the natural range of haemoglobin concentration, e.g.an interquartile range (use summary(haem$hb)) of ~ 11-13g/dL. Visually, this only shifts the intercept on the right hand graph on the plot above by a small amount. But, this is after pcv is controlled for. You can see from the plot that males, for whatever reason, can have higher packed cell volume and in turn this gives them higher average haemoglobin concentration than females. Just looking at haemoglobin concentration versus sex would miss this.

haem.plot2 <- ggplot(data=haem, aes(x=sex,y=hb))

haem.plot2 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("Haemoglobin concentration (g/dL)")
